{"count": 28683, "next": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=868", "previous": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=866", "results": [{"id": 76908, "name": "Robert W. Cort", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 1985872, "title": "Three men and a baby (Captioned)", "work_id": 81489, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1978729, "title": "Three men and a baby", "work_id": 95462, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2258890, "title": "Runaway bride", "work_id": 90564, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 905184, "title": "Mr Holland's opus (Captioned)", "work_id": 85928, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2182772, "title": "Outrageous fortune", "work_id": 95056, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1989865, "title": "Mr. Holland's opus", "work_id": 85469, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "2000-01-01", "date_of_death": "", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 1, "name": "United States of America", "slug": "united-states-of-america"}], "biography": "Robert W. Cort (born January 13, 1951) is an American film producer. Since 1985 he has produced forty-eight feature films which have grossed more than $2.5 billion in worldwide box office. These include: On the Basis of Sex, Three Men and a Baby, Cocktail, Jumanji, Bill & Ted's Excellent Adventure, Revenge of the Nerds II: Nerds in Paradise, The Cutting Edge, Against the Ropes, Runaway Bride, and Save the Last Dance.Cort also produced Mr. Holland's Opus and currently serves on the board of directors for The Mr. Holland's Opus FoundationCort’s HBO film, Something the Lord Made, won three Emmy Awards, including the 2004 Outstanding Film Made for Television. The film also won the American Film Institute Award, the Director's and Writer's Guild Awards, the Christopher, NAACP Image Award and the prestigious Peabody Award. His other television films have also won multiple honors, including the 1990 Emmy for Outstanding Children's Program for A Mother's Courage: The Mary Thomas Story.His production of the family drama Im Winter ein Jahr (English Title: A Year Ago in Winter), won the Silver Lola for Best Picture at the 2009 German Academy Awards.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-08-01T16:52:22.179980+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 5045, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_W._Cort"}], "uuid": "c260c739-9d85-40dc-8e08-763f9601cb47", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "27908", "external_references": [{"id": 26456, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q7350659"}, {"id": 31229, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "38029655"}, {"id": 31230, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "no00076766"}, {"id": 31231, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-no00076766"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-06T00:47:55.966752+10:00"}, {"id": 76907, "name": "William Peters", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2065953, "title": "A Class Divided", "work_id": 81487, "role": "producer/director", "role_id": 31, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "1921-07-30", "date_of_death": "2007-05-20", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 1, "name": "English", "slug": "english"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 1, "name": "United States of America", "slug": "united-states-of-america"}], "biography": "William Ernest Peters Jr. (July 30, 1921 – May 20, 2007) was an American journalist and documentary filmmaker who frequently covered race relations in the United States. His 1956 Redbook magazine article \"Our Weapon Is Love\" introduced the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and the philosophy of nonviolent resistance to the nation.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-08-01T17:28:14.773870+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 5358, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Peters_(journalist)"}], "uuid": "d5718d71-84e1-4134-b5f2-2b038d0e0a53", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "30483", "external_references": [{"id": 25414, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q8016819"}, {"id": 32030, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "85155733"}, {"id": 32031, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "n86069233"}, {"id": 32032, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-n86069233"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-06T02:17:42.139877+10:00"}, {"id": 76906, "name": "Geoff Murphy", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 1985858, "title": "The Quiet Earth", "work_id": 81475, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2277231, "title": "Young guns II (Captioned)", "work_id": 84227, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1995039, "title": "Goodbye pork pie", "work_id": 91014, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1995038, "title": "Goodbye pork pie", "work_id": 91014, "role": "co-producer", "role_id": 915, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1985854, "title": "Utu", "work_id": 81474, "role": "producer/director", "role_id": 31, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "Geoffrey Peter Murphy", "date_of_birth": "1938-10-12", "date_of_death": "2018-12-03", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 1, "name": "English", "slug": "english"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 9, "name": "New Zealand", "slug": "new-zealand"}], "biography": "Geoffrey Peter Murphy  (12 October 1938 – 3 December 2018) was a New Zealand filmmaker, producer, director, and screenwriter best known for his work during the renaissance of New Zealand cinema that began in the second half of the 1970s. His second feature Goodbye Pork Pie (1981) was the first New Zealand film to win major commercial success on its soil. Murphy directed several Hollywood features during the 1990s, before returning to New Zealand as second-unit director on The Lord of the Rings film trilogy. Murphy was also a scriptwriter, special effects technician, schoolteacher and trumpet player at different times . He was married to Merata Mita, a film director, actor, writer.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-08-01T14:56:29.523032+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 2102, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoff_Murphy"}], "uuid": "b9dd127a-4913-42bc-8f88-c34c27639118", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "19504", "external_references": [{"id": 9068, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q1350663"}, {"id": 9069, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "86019369"}, {"id": 9070, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "n92073385"}, {"id": 9071, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-n92073385"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-05T20:01:53.792284+10:00"}, {"id": 76905, "name": "Michael White", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2649397, "title": "The Rocky Horror picture show (Captioned)", "work_id": 81473, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1812102, "title": "The Rocky horror picture show. - [Collector's ed.]", "work_id": 85127, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2000956, "title": "The Rocky Horror picture show", "work_id": 95269, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2475999, "title": "Moonlighting", "work_id": 81688, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "1936-01-16", "date_of_death": "2016-03-07", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name"